steps.prompt_sent:
You are an independent scientific reviewer. Review this manuscript for
methodological correctness. For each error or concern, classify its severity.

SEVERITY CLASSIFICATION (required for every finding):

RETRACTION-WORTHY: The error means the paper's central conclusions CANNOT be
supported by the data as presented. Not "could be improved" — "fundamentally broken."
Examples: data coding errors that change the primary outcome, impossible statistical
values, applying tests that don't match the study design rendering all inferences invalid.

MAJOR-REVISION: A real methodological concern that could change conclusions if
addressed differently, but does NOT definitively invalidate them.
Examples: missing controls, underpowered secondary analyses, questionable but
defensible statistical choices.

MINOR: Valid criticism applicable to most published papers. Would not change conclusions.
Examples: no robustness checks, limited generalizability, minor reporting gaps.

KEY TEST: If confirmed, would this need RETRACTION, REVISION, or just NOTING?

Manuscript:
\documentclass[11pt,a4paper]{article}

\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb}
\usepackage{booktabs}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage[margin=1in]{geometry}
\usepackage{natbib}

\title{Where the overfitting cliff appears in Koide-type quark mass relations}
\author{Andrew M.~Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The charged-lepton Koide relation is unusually precise, but many proposed quark-sector extensions introduce extra freedom absent from the original formula: choice of triple, sign assignment, and evaluation scale. The central question is therefore not whether one can find a close quark-side closure, but where the search crosses from constrained pattern-finding into overfitting.

This note identifies that cliff empirically. The first result is assumption-light: across successive FLAG/PDG releases, the lepton Koide residual tracks improving precision downward, whereas the best-known quark self-scale claims do not. The Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self residual stays near $8\times10^{-3}$, and the Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale residual near $4\times10^{-3}$, while the propagated uncertainty shrinks by roughly a factor of three. On current inputs, both quark residuals remain $9$--$14\,\sigma_Q$ from zero. By contrast, the lepton residual remains of order $1\,\sigma_Q$ and has converged as measurements improved.

The second result is a literature-motivated search audit. We enumerate $20$ quark triples, four sign assignments, and a discrete set of physically interpretable evaluation scales, giving $12{,}960$ trials. In a random-spectrum reference model, the best closure from the full search lies near the median of the null distribution, with empirical tail fraction $T\approx0.50$. Fixed/self-scale single-triple claims rank higher within the same reference class, with $T\approx0.007$ for Cao and $T\approx0.03$ for Rivero. The qualitative lesson is simple: three-point relations at fixed/self scales can still look nontrivial, but once running-scale freedom is admitted, close closures become generic enough that the search has crossed the overfitting cliff.

Finally, we contrast this three-point search with a genuinely more constrained four-point geometric condition based on Descartes/Soddy constructions. In the random-spectrum data, algebraic three-point Koide-like closures are common, whereas joint Koide-plus-Soddy matches are rare. The practical conclusion is therefore qualitative: fixed/self-scale three-point relations may still be worth discussing, running-scale searches are overfit, and constrained four-point constructions occupy a different regime entirely.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Koide observed that the charged-lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e,\mu,\tau)
=
\frac{m_e+m_\mu+m_\tau}
{\left(\sqrt{m_e}+\sqrt{m_\mu}+\sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2}
=
\frac{2}{3},
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to very high precision. That fact has motivated many attempts to extend Koide-like structure to the quark sector. Existing proposals differ not only in which quark triple they use, but also in whether square roots are signed and whether quark masses are evaluated at self scales or at other running scales. The resulting ambiguity is the whole problem: once enough freedom is admitted, a close closure may say more about the search than about the masses.

This paper asks a narrower question than ``is there a true quark Koide relation?'' We ask instead: \emph{where is the overfitting cliff?} In other words, how much freedom can be added before a Koide-style closure stops being genuinely restrictive and starts becoming generic?

The answer appears to have three parts. First, fixed/self-scale three-point relations can still look nontrivial. Second, once one admits running-scale freedom, the best closure found by a broad search is no longer unusual. Third, when one moves from a three-point algebraic relation to a genuinely more constrained four-point geometric relation, accidental matches become rare again. That is the whole story of this note.

Throughout, we write $T$ for the empirical tail fraction of a random-spectrum reference ensemble that produces a closure at least as good as the observed one. We use $T$ as a descriptive rank statistic within a chosen reference class, not as a calibrated significance level.

\section{Temporal trajectory: the assumption-light test}
\label{sec:temporal}

Before introducing any Monte Carlo reference model, one can ask a simpler question. If a mass relation is exact in nature, then as measurements improve, its residual should move toward zero in step with the shrinking propagated uncertainty. If instead the relation is a coincidence on a particular set of central values, then the residual will remain pinned near its accidental value while the uncertainty shrinks past it.

By this test, the charged-lepton Koide relation behaves like a genuine success. The residual has tracked improving precision downward over decades and remains of order $1\,\sigma_Q$. The best-known quark claims do not behave that way. Across the FLAG/PDG release series from 2013 to 2024, the Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self residual remains in the band $7.5$--$8.2\times10^{-3}$, while the Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale residual remains in the band $3.5$--$4.7\times10^{-3}$. Over the same period, the propagated $\sigma_Q$ shrinks by roughly a factor of three. On current values, those residuals sit at about $14\,\sigma_Q$ and $9\,\sigma_Q$, respectively. The lepton case converges; the quark self-scale cases do not.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
Claim & 2013 $|Q-2/3|$ & 2024 $|Q-2/3|$ & 2024 $\sigma_Q$ & 2024 $|r|/\sigma_Q$ & Trend \\
\midrule
Lepton Koide
& $\sim 10^{-5}$ & $6\times10^{-6}$ & $\sim 6\times10^{-6}$ & $\approx 1$
& converging \\

Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed self
& $8.2\times10^{-3}$ & $7.5\times10^{-3}$ & $5.4\times10^{-4}$ & $\approx 14$
& stable; non-convergent \\

Cao $(c,b,t)$ self
& $3.5\times10^{-3}$ & $4.7\times10^{-3}$ & $5.4\times10^{-4}$ & $\approx 9$
& stable / slow drift \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Temporal behavior of the best-known Koide-type claims. The charged-lepton relation improves the way an exact relation should; the quark self-scale claims do not.}
\label{tab:temporal}
\end{table}

This temporal comparison is the most assumption-light evidence in the paper. It does not depend on a prior over random spectra, on a null-model family, or on any look-elsewhere machinery. It already tells us that the best-known quark self-scale claims do not behave like the lepton relation under improving data.

\section{Auditing the search: where the three-point cliff appears}
\label{sec:audit}

The temporal argument does not by itself tell us how much of the literature's apparent structure comes from search freedom. To answer that, we audit a discrete, literature-motivated search space. The search runs over all $20$ three-quark subsets of the six quarks, four sign assignments, and a finite set of physically interpretable evaluation scales, for a total of $12{,}960$ trials. The scale list includes self scales, the standard $2\,\mathrm{GeV}$ reference for light quarks, and selected SM mass scales within perturbative running windows.

The main reference model draws random six-mass spectra from a log-uniform distribution spanning the quark mass range and conditions on perturbative validity under four-loop CRunDec running. For each retained draw, the same $12{,}960$-trial audit is performed. The resulting empirical tail fraction $T$ is the fraction of retained random spectra whose best closure is at least as good as the observed one. This is best read as a rank within the chosen reference class, not as an absolute significance level.

Under this audit, the key result is blunt: \emph{the best hit from the full search is not unusual}. Its empirical tail fraction is $T\approx0.50$, i.e.\ almost exactly what one expects from the middle of the reference distribution. The search as a whole therefore does not uncover a quark-side closure that stands out once the admitted freedom is counted honestly.

At the same time, some fixed/self-scale single-triple claims remain more structured than the full search. In the same reference class, the Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale claim sits at $T\approx0.007$, while the Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self claim sits at $T\approx0.03$. These are not decisive statements about nature, but they do show that limited-flexibility three-point relations are not yet in the same regime as the full running-scale search.

That contrast is the practical answer to the paper's motivating question. The overfitting cliff is not ``all quark Koide numerology.'' The cliff appears when one promotes the evaluation scale itself into a search variable. At that point, very close three-point closures are no longer hard to obtain, and the best result from a broad audit becomes generic rather than informative.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrc}
\toprule
Claim & Trials & $T$ (Model A) \\
\midrule
Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale $(+,+,+)$ & 1 & $0.007$ \\
Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed self & 4 & $0.03$ \\
Full search & $12{,}960$ & $0.50$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Claim-level ranking within the audited random-spectrum reference class. Fixed/self-scale single-triple claims can still look nontrivial; the full running-scale search does not.}
\label{tab:ranking}
\end{table}

\section{An assumption-light restatement: counting sub-$\sigma_Q$ hits}
\label{sec:hits}

The same point can be stated without leaning heavily on the random-spectrum prior. Across the audited $12{,}960$ trials, only $8$ configurations produce residuals with $|Q-2/3|<\sigma_Q$. A parametric bootstrap around the observed masses yields an expectation of about $7$ such hits. In other words, once the search is run at full freedom, the number of apparently interesting closures is already what one would expect from perturbations of the measured masses themselves.

This is not the same as the random-spectrum audit, but it points in the same direction: the full running-scale search is not finding a surprising abundance of structure. It is finding about as many near-hits as the current measurement-noise scale already allows.

\section{Beyond the cliff: four-point geometric constraints}
\label{sec:geometry}

The three-point story is not the whole story. A natural counter-question is whether all mass numerology becomes trivial once enough freedom is admitted, or whether one can recover genuine rarity by imposing a stricter structure.

To test that, we compared the three-point algebraic search with a four-point geometric condition based on Descartes/Soddy circle constructions. In the baseline random-spectrum ensemble, approximately $60.7\%$ of draws contain at least one Koide-like triple satisfying a loose closure criterion. So three-point algebraic closures are common in random data. But when one further demands that a Soddy mass derived from such a triple match one of the remaining masses, the rate collapses: only $8$ of $10{,}000$ draws satisfy the joint condition at $0.1\%$ tolerance. Joint Koide-plus-Soddy matches are therefore hundreds of times rarer than Koide-like triples alone.

That contrast matters. It shows that ``three-point closure made common by search freedom'' and ``four-point geometric structure that remains rare in random spectra'' are empirically distinguishable regimes. The problem is not numerology in the abstract. The problem is unconstrained numerology.

\section{What this paper does and does not claim}
\label{sec:scope}

This paper does \emph{not} prove that no quark mass relation reflects underlying structure. It does not claim that a particular random-spectrum prior is fundamental. It does not attempt to bound every unenumerable degree of freedom in four decades of Koide-style speculation.

What it does claim is narrower and, I think, more defensible.

First, the known quark self-scale claims do not improve under measurement updates the way the lepton Koide relation does. Second, a broad three-point search with running-scale freedom produces a best hit that is typical within the audited reference class. Third, a more constrained four-point geometric condition is much rarer in random data than three-point algebraic closure. Those three facts are enough to locate the cliff. Fixed/self-scale three-point relations may still be discussable; running-scale searches are overfit; constrained four-point constructions deserve to be treated separately.

\section{Conclusion}

The central question of this note was not whether one can write down a quark Koide-like formula, but where such formulas stop being restrictive. The answer is that the decisive variable is search freedom.

At fixed or self scales, some three-point quark claims still rank unusually within a random-spectrum reference class, even though their present residuals are far from zero in units of current measurement precision. Once running-scale freedom is admitted, however, the broad three-point search crosses the overfitting cliff: the best closure found by the full audit lies near the median of the null distribution. By contrast, when one imposes a genuinely more constrained four-point geometric condition, accidental matches become rare again.

So the practical lesson is simple. The interesting dividing line is not ``leptons versus quarks.'' It is \emph{constraint versus freedom}. Three-point fixed/self-scale relations can still look nontrivial. Running-scale selection makes close three-point closures generic. Four-point geometric constraints are different.

\section*{Computational note}

All numerical results are reproducible from the accompanying repository. The audited search consists of $12{,}960$ trials built from $20$ quark triples, four sign assignments, and a discrete set of physically interpretable evaluation scales. Model~A uses four-loop \texttt{CRunDec} running with a log-uniform random-spectrum reference class conditioned on perturbative validity; the main run uses $N=100{,}000$ retained draws. Model~B is a parametric bootstrap around the observed FLAG/PDG masses and $\alpha_s$, used only for the sub-$\sigma_Q$ hit-count comparison. The four-point geometric test is applied to the same random-spectrum ensemble.

\begin{thebibliography}{99}

\bibitem{Koide1982}
Y.~Koide, Lett.\ Nuovo Cim.\ \textbf{34}, 201 (1982).

\bibitem{Koide1983}
Y.~Koide, Phys.\ Rev.\ D \textbf{28}, 252 (1983).

\bibitem{Rivero2011}
A.~Rivero, arXiv:1111.7232 [hep-ph] (2011).

\bibitem{RZ2011}
W.~Rodejohann and H.~Zhang, arXiv:1101.5525 [hep-ph] (2011).

\bibitem{Cao2012}
F.~G.~Cao, Phys.\ Rev.\ D \textbf{85}, 113003 (2012).

\bibitem{CRunDec}
F.~Herren and M.~Steinhauser, Comput.\ Phys.\ Commun.\ \textbf{224}, 333 (2018).

\bibitem{FLAG2024}
Y.~Aoki et al.\ (FLAG), Phys.\ Rev.\ D \textbf{113}, 014508 (2026), arXiv:2411.04268.

\bibitem{PDG2024}
S.~Navas et al.\ (PDG), Phys.\ Rev.\ D \textbf{110}, 030001 (2024).

\bibitem{RepoMC}
A.~M.~Brilliant, ``mass\_as\_curvature\_mc\_v3: Look-elsewhere analysis code,'' GitHub (2026).

\end{thebibliography}

\end{document}

